{
  "answer": "In Allama Iqbal's poem \"Maa ka Khwab\" (The Mother's Dream), from *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, the mother dreams of seeing her son among a silent procession of boys dressed in emerald green robes, each carrying a burning lamp, as they move through darkness to an unknown destination.[^1] Her son lags at the back with a slow pace and no lamp (which has been extinguished by her tears).[^2] He explains to her that her constant weeping over his absence harms his spiritual progress.[^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 (\"Maa ka Khwab\"), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-1d110a).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 (\"Maa ka Khwab\"), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-2fb543).\n\n[^3]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, ch. 29 (\"Maa ka Khwab\"), [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/29-maa-ka-khwab/translation/#p-4feffc).",
